===Etymology===
{{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|acorne|lang=enm}}, an alteration (after {{term|corn}}) of earlier {{term|akern|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term|æcern||acorn, oak-mast|lang=ang}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{recons|akraną|lang=gem-pro}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{recons|h₂ógeh₂-||berry|lang=ine-pro}}. Cognate with Saterland Frisian {{term|Äkkene|lang=stq}}, Flemish {{term|aker|lang=nl}}, Danish {{term|agern|lang=da}}; and with Irish {{term|áirne||sloe|lang=ga}}, Lithuanian {{term|uoga|úoga|lang=lt}}, Russian {{term|ягода||berry|tr=jágoda|lang=ru}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{audio|en-us-acorn.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# The [[fruit]] of the [[oak]], being an oval [[nut]] growing in a woody cup or [[cupule]].
# {{context|nautical}} A cone-shaped piece of wood on the point of the spindle above the vane, on the mast-head.
# {{context|zoology}} See ''[[acorn-shell]]''.

